    Yes, I have also misunderstood the syncing of fork with the upstream repository as well.

    If I understood it correctly from what you say, the correct way to pull the upstream repository to the local copy, these are the steps to follow it:

    Using of SourceTree

    1. Go to repository setting

    1. Shows you the remote repository path, add an remote path of the upstream to the setting

    1. Image of adding the upstream path, and clicking Ok.

    1. Fetch the commits from the upstream repo and check it is correct commits

    1. Pull the commits from the upstream repository master, this will make local changes in your local repository

    2. Push the local copy repository back to your own remote repository

    Using of Command Line interface [a rough idea, do check the command for these usage]

    1. git remote add upstream https://github.com/AY1920S2-CS2113T-M16-2/tp.git

    You can check by "git remote -v"

    1. git fetch upstream master

    2. git pull upstream master

    3. git push origin master

    Hello here's my suggestion for the three if-else cases 😃

    1. define max and min values in your budget class

    final static double MAX = 5000;

    final static double MIN = 0;

    1. The empty constructor initializes budget to zero

    public Budget(){

    this.amount = 0;

    }

    1. set budget relies on min/max value (handles negative values too!) 🥂

    public void setBudget(double amount){

    if(amount > 5000){

    this.amount = Math.min(amount,MAX);

    }else{

    this.amount = Math.max(amount,0);

    }

    }

    Actually, I previously found that the data structure of our 'AvailableModulesList' is quite messy. You can simply understand it as there are actually two 'availableModulesList' in this class.

    • One is the 'AvailableModulesList' self which extends 'ModuleList'.

    • But I find there is another 'static ModuleList availableModulesList' in the 'AvailableModulesList' object. And the constructor add the modules in the database to this 'availableModulesList'.

    It is ok to keep the second static list in the object because it is class-level and other methods can get 'availableModulesList' easily through this class-level static variable. But it caused a problem we need to notice:

    when we use 'availableModulesList.add(X)' in other method, actually it is added to the first list(self) I mentioned above. So I override the 'add' method in 'AvailableModulesList'.

    ' @Override

    public boolean add(Module module) {

    availableModulesList.add(module);

    return super.add(module);

}'

    So to solve the potential problem, you may need to override the delete method in 'AvailableModulesList'.

    We should separate Class and Tasks because they are different things essentially.

    1. They use different data types, making the generic will cause issues. When parsing date, one is an actual date while another is a day of the week. Following your idea of converting it into a LocalDate or Date, it will not be very wise to keep inserting it (lets say run a loop to add it for 13 weeks). I personally don't think it's a good implementation to make it general and give tasks an arraylist for their date or time when they only need one variable.

    I propose that they should be separate systems. So Tasks and Timetable are separate. Timetable will have its own features with class schedule. Makes it easier to list or do other operations for each.

    When doing the calendar feature which counted items in tasklist, I thought it was not very practical to mix both class and task items in the same list, because attending class is different from a task. We add classes in bulk, but tasks are much more adhoc.

    As a user, I can have my timetable printed out or have it placed static else where, or even memorise it. Why have repeated items keep occurring in the task list? It will dilute the intention of having a "todo" list.

    What do you think?

    I have fixed this.

    My design idea:

    1. Make class,task having the same stored format in taskList. A task can also has multiple schedule which means task can also has mutiple location, data,time.

    2. The difference is in input format for date.

    class and task accepted time: 11:00-1:00 a time range. This is how our calender normally designed.

    class accepts date: integer from 1-7(Mon - Sun) This will then be tranferred to the date in this week. So it will be stored like: 2020 - 04 -05

    task accepts date: date format: 2020 - 04 - 05. It will also be stored like: 2020 - 04 - 05

    The easier version can be:

    delete t/hh:mm-hh:mm: delete task within this time range

    delete t/hh:mm: delete task whose time range contains this time

    delete d/yyyy-mm-dd: delete task on that day

    Can either implement them all or just implement one of them. As long as there is no bug when user uses it, it is good enough.

    list d/yyyy-mm-dd: only list tasks on that day

    list t/hh:mm-hh:mm: list tasks/class within that time range

    e.g. A task: t/11:00-12:00 will be listed

    By command t/10:00-12:00

    Optional:

    list d/yyyy-mm-dd t/hh:mm-hh:mm: list tasks has within that date+time range

    e.g. A task: d/2020-02-02 t/11:00-12:00 will be listed

    By command list d/2020-02-02 t/10:00-12:00

    list d/yyyy-mm-dd t/hh:mm-hh:mm c/sth: list tasks has within that date+time range and is in category sth

    e.g. A task: d/2020-02-02 t/11:00-12:00 c/TODO will be listed

    By command list d/2020-02-02 t/10:00-12:00 c/TODO

    delete d/yyyy-mm-dd: only delete tasks on that day

    delete t/hh:mm-hh:mm: delete tasks/class within that time range

    e.g. A task: t/11:00-12:00 will be deleted

    By command delete t/10:00-12:00

    Optional:

    delete d/yyyy-mm-dd t/hh:mm-hh:mm: delete tasks has within that date+time range

    e.g. A task: d/2020-02-02 t/11:00-12:00 will be deleted

    By command delete d/2020-02-02 t/10:00-12:00

    delete d/yyyy-mm-dd t/hh:mm-hh:mm c/sth: delete tasks has within that date+time range and is in category sth

    e.g. A task: d/2020-02-02 t/11:00-12:00 c/TODO will be deleted

    By command delete d/2020-02-02 t/10:00-12:00 c/TODO

    I see, thanks for the clarification. Do you think it would be better if we accept duplicate headers, but it only process the latest duplicate.

    This is because perhaps next time when the user has typed a lot of stuff, and realizes that somewhere at the front he had a typo. So instead of retyping the commands, he can simply duplicate the header with the correct information.

    For example: John is 43 years old.

    addp \age 34 \name Peter \address Pasir Ris \phone 1234567 \age 43 \name John

    The user has mistakenly entered age as 34 and name as Peter. With this, he can easily amend it by duplicating the age and name header and inputting it the correct information.

    done except for "add using link" command

    We are currently passing the reference of private instance variables of our main class MeetingOrganizer into methods of another class Command, in order to modify the private instance variables. However, this doesnt seem to be a good idea (refer to mistake #3 in https://dzone.com/articles/java-getter-and-setter-basics-common-mistakes-and), as we are modifying a private instance variable directly, outside of its class.

    The right way modify a private instance variable is to use both getter and setter. In the getter, return a copy of the private instance variable. In the setter, copy the passed values to the private instance variable.

    However in this case where it does not make sense to create MeetingOrganizer object in the Command class, we cannot use getter and setter in the Command class. Hence we are passing the reference of the private instance variables.

    Is there a better way? Or perhaps we shouldn't have a separate Command class that modifies the private instance variables of the main class MeetingOrganizer?
